day medievalists regard it as an undisputed fact that Arabic culture – especially science – influenced the Latin Middle Ages in a multitude of ways. However, more detailed research is needed into the conditions, background and context of this ‘cultural exchange’, a task undertaken by the present volume in 44 papers from a variety of disciplines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aIslamic learning and scholarshipxHistoryvCongresses. 0aLearning and scholarshipxHistoryyMedieval, 500-1500vCongresses. 0aPhilosophy, MedievalxIslamic influencesvCongresses. 4aArabien. 4aEuropa. 4aMittelalter. 4aWissenstransfer. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Medieval.2bisacsh  aArabia.  aEurope.  aMiddle Ages.  atransfer of knowledge.1 aBláhová, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrague, Rémi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurnett, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDi Giovanni, Matteo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrews, Wolfram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD’Ancona, Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnders, Markus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFidora, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFijalkowski, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGensler, Marek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuerrero, Rafael Ramón, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuldentops, Guy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutas, Dimitri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular